Now I have all the context needed. Let me output my evaluations.

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNV_</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>Valid bug. The meta render passes `src=${args.src ?? ''}` and `sprite-url=${args.spriteUrl ?? ''}`, which binds empty strings when values are undefined. This causes the component to see `src=""` (not undefined) and trigger inline mode incorrectly. Fix by switching to property bindings (`.src`, `.spriteUrl`) so undefined values don't set attributes.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Replace attribute bindings `src=${args.src ?? ''}` and `sprite-url=${args.spriteUrl ?? ''}` with property bindings `.src=${args.src}` and `.spriteUrl=${args.spriteUrl}` in the meta render function.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWG</thread_id>
  <decision>deny</decision>
  <reasoning>The bot says rem fallback literals violate the token-only rule, but existing components (hx-button, hx-badge, etc.) consistently use rem/px hardcoded last-resort fallbacks throughout their styles (e.g., `var(--hx-space-2, 0.5rem)`, `var(--hx-border-radius-md, 0.375rem)`). The feedback contradicts established, reviewed project patterns. Removing fallbacks would cause invisible icons if tokens don't load.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>N/A - denied</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWK</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>`display: contents` on `.icon__inline` is a real accessibility regression. The span carries `role="img"` and `aria-label`/`aria-hidden` from the component. `display: contents` removes the element from the accessibility tree in some browsers, making the ARIA attributes ineffective. This is a WCAG 2.1 AA violation risk for a healthcare application.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Replace `display: contents` with `display: inline-flex; width: 100%; height: 100%;` on `.icon__inline` to preserve both layout and accessibility tree presence.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWP</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>The sanitizer is security-sensitive code and has zero test coverage. The project's zero-tolerance rule says "No untested code — Every component, every utility, every public API has tests." The sanitization of `on*` attributes, `<script>` elements, and potentially `javascript:` URIs must be tested. Fetch can be mocked with `vi.fn()` in Vitest browser mode.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Add test suite covering: (1) src attribute reflects to property, (2) empty src treated as absent, (3) sanitizer strips `<script>` elements, (4) sanitizer strips `on*` attributes, (5) sanitizer strips `javascript:` href values, using `vi.spyOn(globalThis, 'fetch')` mock.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWS</thread_id>
  <decision>deny</decision>
  <reasoning>ElementInternals is only appropriate for form-associated custom elements. hx-icon is a purely decorative/informational component with no form participation. The existing non-form components in this library (hx-avatar, hx-badge, hx-card, hx-breadcrumb) all correctly omit ElementInternals. Adding it without `static formAssociated = true` and form lifecycle methods would be dead code that violates the "no orphaned code" rule.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>N/A - denied</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWW</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>Real race condition: if `src` changes rapidly (e.g., user cycles through icon names), a slow first fetch can resolve after a fast second fetch and overwrite the correct state with stale data. The `_fetchedSrc` guard only prevents duplicate fetches for the same URL, not out-of-order responses. A sequence counter fixes this properly.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Add `private _fetchSeq = 0` counter. Increment before each fetch, capture the value, and guard the state assignment with `if (seq !== this._fetchSeq) return;` after each `await`.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWd</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>CRITICAL security issue. The sanitizer only removes `<script>` children and `on*` event attributes on child elements, but: (1) `on*` attributes on the root `<svg>` itself (e.g., `onload`) are not stripped, (2) `javascript:` and `data:` URIs in `href`/`xlink:href`/`src` attributes on any element are not blocked, (3) `<foreignObject>` embedding arbitrary HTML is not removed. This is an XSS vector in a healthcare application — must fix.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Extend sanitization to: (1) strip `on*` attrs from the root svg element, (2) remove `<foreignObject>` and `<use>` elements referencing external URLs, (3) strip any attribute whose value matches `^javascript:` or `^data:` (case-insensitive) on href/xlink:href/src attributes across all elements including root.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWl</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>Valid bug. `this.src !== undefined` treats `src=""` as inline mode, suppressing sprite rendering. When `src` is bound as an empty string (e.g., from a template that sets `src=""`), the component enters inline mode but renders nothing (since `_inlineSvg` is empty), hiding a perfectly valid `name`-based sprite icon. The check should require a non-empty string.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Change `if (this.src !== undefined)` to `if (typeof this.src === 'string' && this.src.trim().length > 0)` in the `render()` method.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

<thread_evaluation>
  <thread_id>PRRT_kwDORRAfU85yKNWp</thread_id>
  <decision>accept</decision>
  <reasoning>test-results/.last-run.json records local test run state and should not be committed. It creates non-deterministic diffs (different pass/fail states per developer machine) and pollutes the PR with noise. It should be gitignored.</reasoning>
  <planned_fix>Add `test-results/` to `.gitignore` and remove the file from tracking with `git rm --cached test-results/.last-run.json`.</planned_fix>
</thread_evaluation>

